[5] Malaysia, Singapore
Date: Sat 15 Jan 2005
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Borneo Bulletin Online [edited]
<http://www.brunei-online.com/bb/fri/jan14w1.htm>

Malaysia
----------
Malaysia's Health Minister, Chua Soi Lek, announced a doubling in dengue
cases last month [December 2004], from an average of 450 a week to about
1000, with the increase especially noticeable in the modern capital Kuala
Lumpur. 12 people have died from dengue fever since November [2004].
Abandoned building projects and construction sites, found to be the main
dengue culprits in Malaysia, will be targeted in a clean-up campaign to be
launched in the capital in an effort to stamp out the menace. Chua said
owners of a total of 14 186 premises had been fined and 59 people brought
to court last year [2004], after mosquitoes were found breeding in their
compounds.
[The ministry issued an alert for the capital, Kuala Lumpur, and Selangor
state on 2 Jan 2005; see ref. 2005 (01) below. - Mod.JW]
Singapore
----------
Singaporean authorities recorded more than 8500 dengue cases in 2004, a
10-year high and almost double the number in 2003. Starting next month
[February 2005], the city-state plans to impose fines on homeowners found
with mosquitoes breeding on their premises. Private homes, rather than
construction sites, are the main breeding grounds of mosquitoes in
Singapore, and 1st-time offenders will be fined the equivalent of 60 US
dollars, and double that for the next offence.
Most Singaporeans live in apartment buildings, but many families keep
potted plants and other receptacles in which mosquitoes can breed.
Penalties for construction sites where mosquitoes are found breeding are
much stiffer and can include up to 6 months in jail for those responsible.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
