[6] Malaysia (Penang)
Date: Sat 15 Jan 2005
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Penang Online, 14 Jan 2005 [edited]
<http://penang.thestar.com.my/content/news/2005/1/14/9895231.asp>

70 cases of dengue detected in Penang
-----------------------------------------
Health authorities here have detected 70 dengue cases over the last 2
weeks. State Health, Welfare and Caring Society committee chairman P. K.
Subbaiyah, however, stressed that the increasing number of cases was not
due to the recent tsunami. "From past records, there is usually a sudden
surge in dengue cases every 4 years. This is a normal occurrence here and
has nothing to do with the tsunami," he told a press conference here
yesterday [13 Jan 2005].
Subbaiyah said the reported cases came from all over Penang island,
including Sungai Gelugor and Taman Bukit Jambul, the Penang Prison and the
Bandar Baru Air Itam police quarters. Whenever 2 or more cases are reported
in a particular area, surveillance and preventive measures would
immediately be intensified, he said.
At the end of last year [2004], a total of 1767 cases were reported,
compared to 733 cases in 2003.
"An area with suspected dengue cases will be fogged within 24 hours and
again after 7 days," he said.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Penang island, off the west coast of peninsular Malaysia, is a popular
tourist destination, with a temple dedicated to snakes and other sights.
Dengue control there appears to be soundly based. - Mod.JW]
