[8] Malaysia 2004
Date: Sat 15 Jan 2005
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: News Straits Times, Malaysia 15 Jan 2005 [edited]
<http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Saturday/National/NST32210451.txt/Article/indexb_html>

[University] undergraduates and schoolchildren are the most susceptible to
dengue fever, because they are active when Aedes mosquitoes feed. Some 53
percent of the 11 621 confirmed cases of dengue fever and dengue
hemorrhagic fever [DHF] last year [2004] were children and youths up to the
age of 24, said the Health Ministry's Communicable Disease Control Division.
Of these 6199 children and youths, roughly three-quarters were those aged
between 10 and 24 years. There were 33 025 suspected dengue cases last year
[2004].
Dr. Ramlee Rahmat, a director of the division, said a health ministry study
found students with dengue fever were bitten on university campuses and
during indoor and outdoor recreational activities. School children could
have been bitten in school buses and other vehicles, or, in school. They
could have also been bitten in the evening during outdoor activities and
when returning home from school, he added. "We are seriously concerned over
children becoming victims. School bus operators have been asked to use
aerosol insecticide before picking up children in the morning and school
managements to destroy all Aedes mosquito breeding grounds," Dr. Ramlee
said. The same goes for students in institutions of higher learning. Just 2
days ago, Health Minister Datuk Dr Chua Soi Lek said that schools were a
major breeding ground for Aedes mosquitoes, having been left empty during
the long school holidays.
Ramlee warned that fogging to kill mosquitoes was limited in its
effectiveness against the outbreak, giving "a false sense of security."
Larvae would still develop into adult mosquitoes, which would lengthen the
dengue outbreak. "Fogging is only a stop-gap measure to prevent more people
in one area from being victims of the disease," he said. So far, mosquitoes
have not become resistant to the chemicals used for fogging. However,
fogging should be closely supervised by health officials to ensure that it
is not haphazard, which could eventually lead to resistance, he added.
The week of 2-8 Jan 2005 saw a slight drop of 2.6 percent in the number of
suspected cases reported overall, to 1049 from 1077 the previous week.
However, the number of cases could rise again if proper measures, such as
destroying breeding grounds, were not taken, Dr. Ramlee said. Selangor
remained the state with the highest number of cases, which rose for the
period to 501 from 469 the previous week.
Penang, Johor, Pahang and Kedah [states] also saw more cases, while in
Kuala Lumpur and Perak, the number of cases fell substantially. Cases in
Penang rose to 70 from 62, Johor to 78 from 58, Pahang to 40 from 31, and
Kedah to 27 from 20. Cases in Kuala Lumpur dropped about 17 percent to 207
from 249, while in Perak, they fell to 12 from 82. Putrajaya has seen 8
cases so far this year [2005], against a total of 213 cases last year.
[A] 6-year-old is the 1st victim to succumb to the disease [die] this year
[2005]. Last year [2004] saw 58 deaths reported.
In checks by authorities, construction sites topped the list of areas found
with mosquito breeding grounds, followed by factories and vacant land. Dr.
Ramlee said the World Health Organization representative for Malaysia,
Singapore and Brunei has been in touch about the outbreak. "I informed him
Malaysia was taking the risk management approach. We want people, including
tourists, to know that we are taking all measures to keep the situation
under control. "Malaysia is still safe for tourists," Dr. Ramlee stressed.
--
